abstractNote = {Aquathermolysis was defined as the overall set of chemical processes that can result from contacting heavy oil or oil sands with high temperature water, whatever the phase. Studies were conducted to demonstrate that the aquathermolytic chemical processes play a significant role in in-situ steam stimulation and that the results of such chemical processes can be important in the development and production of heavy oils and oil sands. Significant chemical reaction was shown to occur between oil sands and water (steam) in the temperature range of 200-300 degrees C. Thermal cracking was only significant above 300 degrees C. The primary sand reaction involved reactive mineral carbonates yielding varying amounts of CO{sub 2} which could affect the acidity of the system and the viscosity of the oil by dissolving in it. It was shown that aquathermolysis can effect the production of H{sub 2}S gas, viscosity of produced oil and maturation of the regions of the reservoir around the production zone. 35 refs., 5 tabs., 24 figs.},
